The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 A truck driver was injured after he rammed the vehicle into a CESC feeder box at the crossing of Diamond Harbour Road and Sahapur Road late on Wednesday evening. Police said the driver, Subhash Yadav, 27, had lost control of the vehicle. He was rescued and admitted to Vidyasagar Hospital by local residents. 

 In another mishap, a man in his late 20s was injured after being knocked down by a private bus at the crossing of Amherst Street and Surya Sen Street on Wednesday afternoon. Sukumar Halder was admitted to Medical College and Hospital. The driver was arrested and the bus impounded. 

 Around 280 litres of illicit foreign liquor was seized from a godown in Bamungachi, under Liluah police station, on Wednesday afternoon. Safikul Islam, 25, from Murshidabad, was arrested during the raid, conducted by a team comprising police and excise officers.

 Governor Gopal Krishna Gandhi visited Gandhi Ashram, in Barrackpore, on Wednesday to review the renovation going on for the past one-and-a-half-months. The ashram has a rare collection of articles used by Mahatma Gandhi.

 A national-level seminar on Right to Information will be organised at Max Mueller Bhavan on Saturday. Information commissioners from West Bengal, Gujarat and another state will attend the seminar. Among the issues to be raised is why people in several states are kept in the dark about the law.

 Employees in the conservancy department of the Calcutta Municipal Corporation will soon be provided with a uniform, civic commissioner Alapan Bandyopadhyay said on Wednesday. There are around 12,000 workers in the department.

 Two alleged criminals were arrested at Sonarpur railway station on Tuesday night. Cash and jewellery worth more than Rs 1 lakh were seized from them. They reportedly told the Government Railway Police that the valuables were looted from a house.

 Two persons were arrested in East Jadavpur on Wednesday on charges of duping around a dozen people. S.N. Gupta, superintendent of police, South 24-Parganas, said the duo took money from the victims promising them insurance policies or jobs.

